  <div class="container">
    <article>
      <h2>Why Terrace Waterproofing Matters</h2>
      <p>Your terrace takes the full impact of weather every day. Over time, cracks develop and water starts entering the slab. Terrace leakage is the <strong>#1 cause of ceiling dampness</strong>. Ignoring it can lead to long-term structural damage.</p>

      <div class="highlight-box">
        <strong>Quick Note:</strong> If you see damp patches on the top floor after rain, it usually means water is already moving through the slab—not just surface moisture.
      </div>

      <h2>Signs You Need Terrace Waterproofing</h2>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Sign</th>
            <th>What It Typically Means</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Ceiling paint peeling</strong></td>
            <td>Moisture trapped in the slab/ceiling layer</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Damp patches on top floor</strong></td>
            <td>Seepage spreading through the roof slab</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Water dripping during rain</strong></td>
            <td>Active leakage through cracks/joints</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td><strong>Cracks on terrace floor</strong></td>
            <td>Thermal movement + wear opening pathways for water</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>Our Terrace Waterproofing System</h2>
      <p>We use high-performance waterproof coatings that expand and contract with temperature changes. Depending on your terrace condition, the solution can include:</p>

      <div class="highlight-box" style="padding: 26px;">
        <ul style="margin: 0; padding-left: 18px;">
          <li><strong>Crack filling treatment</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Polymer waterproof coating</strong></li>
          <li><strong>UV resistant top coating</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Tile joint sealing</strong></li>
          <li><strong>Slope correction</strong> (if needed)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

